    shopifyVariantId: "gid://shopify/ProductVariant/47805370007772",
    name: "ACE-031",
    category: "Immune & Wellness",
    categorySlug: "immune",
    tagline: "Soluble activin receptor that blocks myostatin and promotes muscle preservation",
    description: "ACE-031 is a soluble form of the activin type IIB receptor fused to an IgG-Fc domain. It acts as a decoy receptor, trapping myostatin, activin, and GDF-11 before they can signal through cellular receptors, promoting muscle mass retention.",
    longDescription: "ACE-031 (also called ACVR2B-Fc or RAP-031, MW approximately 90 kDa) is a recombinant fusion protein consisting of the extracellular domain of the human activin type IIB receptor (ActRIIB) fused to the Fc portion of human IgG1. Developed by Acceleron Pharma (now part of Merck) in collaboration with the Salk Institute, ACE-031 functions as a soluble decoy receptor that circulates in the bloodstream, trapping and neutralizing multiple members of the TGF-beta superfamily before they can engage cellular receptors.\n\nThe primary ligands targeted by ACE-031 include myostatin (GDF-8, Kd approximately 0.8 nM), activin A (Kd approximately 0.3 nM), activin B, and GDF-11 (Kd approximately 0.5 nM). All of these are potent negative regulators of skeletal muscle mass that signal through the ActRIIB/ALK4/ALK5 pathway to activate Smad2/3 transcription factors, which in turn suppress muscle protein synthesis and promote protein degradation via the ubiquitin-proteasome and autophagy-lysosome systems. By sequestering these ligands, ACE-031 removes the brakes on muscle growth and maintenance.\n\nIn a Phase 1 study in healthy postmenopausal women (Attie et al., Muscle & Nerve, 2013), a single subcutaneous dose of ACE-031 (0.02-3 mg/kg) produced dose-dependent increases in lean body mass and thigh muscle volume. At the 3 mg/kg dose, thigh muscle volume increased by 3.3% (measured by MRI) and total lean mass increased by 1.0 kg within 29 days. Simultaneously, fat mass decreased by 0.4 kg, and bone formation biomarkers (bone-specific alkaline phosphatase, P1NP) increased significantly, suggesting anabolic effects on bone as well as muscle.\n\nACE-031 was advanced to Phase 2 clinical trials for Duchenne muscular dystrophy (DMD), a devastating X-linked genetic disorder characterized by progressive muscle wasting due to absence of dystrophin. In DMD patients, ACE-031 demonstrated significant increases in lean body mass and improvements in bone mineral density after multiple doses. However, the trial was voluntarily paused after some patients experienced epistaxis (nosebleeds) and telangiectasia (dilated blood vessels), which were attributed to ACE-031's binding of BMP-9 and BMP-10, ligands involved in vascular homeostasis and angiogenesis.\n\nThis experience led to the development of next-generation molecules with more selective ligand-trapping profiles. ACE-083, a locally-acting version that targets individual muscles rather than systemic circulation, advanced in clinical trials for facioscapulohumeral dystrophy (FSHD). Separately, ACE-536 (luspatercept/Reblozyl), which preferentially traps GDF-11 and activin B while sparing BMP-9/10, was FDA-approved for treatment of anemia in myelodysplastic syndromes, validating the ligand-trap therapeutic platform.\n\nPharmacokinetically, ACE-031 has a long circulating half-life of approximately 10-14 days due to the IgG1 Fc domain, which engages the neonatal Fc receptor (FcRn) for recycling. This allows dosing every 2-4 weeks. Peak serum concentrations occur 3-7 days after subcutaneous injection. The molecule is cleared through standard IgG catabolic pathways and does not undergo hepatic metabolism.\n\nFor research use, ACE-031 should be stored lyophilized at -20C or below. Reconstitute with sterile water to the desired concentration and use immediately or store at 2-8C for up to 7 days. Avoid repeated freeze-thaw cycles. As a large protein, ACE-031 requires cold-chain handling and cannot be administered orally (would be degraded by GI proteases).\n\nACE-031 remains an important research tool for studying the TGF-beta superfamily in muscle biology, cachexia, sarcopenia, and bone metabolism. Its broad ligand-trapping profile, while limiting its clinical development, makes it uniquely valuable for research contexts where simultaneous blockade of multiple negative regulators of muscle growth is desired.",
